Fixed the OUTPUT command *again*.  This was much harder than it looked.  It
was a REALLY BAD idea to let \N, \B, \L be special for this command, because
there is practically no way to reconcile these with the regular prefixing
rules.  To work around, I stooped to some pretty disgusting byte-stuffing
tricks that seem to make it possible to keep the advertised syntax, yet still
allow strings such as "\N0" to be OUTPUT (e.g. to modems for which this is a
command), and still permit expansion of variables such as \%a.  It was the
OUTPUT'ing of backslashes, and in particular multiple backslashes and strings
like "\N0", that had been broken up till now.  There are still some minor
