Fixed i/o routines in ckutio.c -- myfillbuf(), myread(), ttinl(), etc, to pass
up proper return codes when network connection is broken.  Now "set host *"
server pops back to prompt if client hangs up.  This way, user can run a
script like "while true { set host * 2000, server }".

However, ttyfd is still > -1 and Kermit thinks the connection is still open.
Extensive tests on SunOS show that under these conditions, no system calls
return any kind of error: ioctl(ttyfd,FIONREAD,&foo) succeeds (but says zero
chars are available); read(ttyfd,1,buf) returns 0; in both cases, errno is set
to zero.  So the system does not tell us "connection reset by peer".  So in
the UNIX version of ttinl(), I added a check: if the read() returns 0 and it's
a network connection AND the timeout was 0 (as it is in server command wait),
it must be a closed connection, so it is safe to close our end too, thus
setting ttyfd to -1 and making everything else work as expected.  However,
this does not catch a hangup during a file transfer.  So I tried removing the
"timeout == 0" condition, reasoning that a network read that did not time out
would never return(0).  This did the trick on SunOS, but it might cause
problems on System V platforms where we have nonblocking reads.  Let's
try... (hours later...)  On UnixWare 2.03, after a lot of finagling, it's OK.
The crucial point is that incoming connections won't work without select(), so
if SELECT is not defined, then NOLISTEN is automatically defined too.  So now
we've compiled and executing this code on SunOS (BSD), UnixWare (System V),
and VMS (UCX).  ckcnet.c, 28 Aug 96.  Later, twiddled #ifdefs further to get
it compiled under AIX 4.1.  Changed AIX 4.1 makefile entry to define SELECT;
made a new entry for UnixWare 2.xx to include SELECT.  Compiled ok on AOS/VS
too (but no incoming TCP).

