Based on experience transferring big files between NYC and the Czech Republic
and the Netherlands via very unpredictable Internet connections, added small
refinements to packet reading code: in input(), if we are about to give up
because of too many retries, first call ttchk() to see if anything is waiting
to be read -- in that case, go read it instead of giving up.  And...  since
the round-trip timer calculation was only done when a packet was successfully
received, we would tend to error out on timeouts once we got the first
timeout.  Now, if we get a timeout or other error, we bump up the timeout
interval.  It's still not perfect, though, because we also want to avoid the
situation in which we time out while in the middle of reading a perfectly good
packet.  But the alarm()/signal()/setjmp()/longjmp() structure of ttinl()
makes it almost impossible to handle that one.  18 May 96.

