While testing Kermit file transfer performance on a very bad connection, in
which 80-90% of all packets get damaged, it was observed that the timeouts
quickly rise to ridiculous levels.  This is, in general, to be expected since
the timeout is based on the time between when a packet is sent and its ACK is
received.  To alleviate the situation, the following adjustments were made to
the timeout calculation:

 . The packet's time stamp is updated if we retransmit it.  Previously, it
   was set only when it was first transmitted.

 . When sending a NAK for packet n, update timestamp of packet n-1 (mod 64),
   which is the ACK or NAK we sent for the previous packet, since this is
   how the file receiver determines round-trip delay.

The problem is that there is no good way for the file sender to distinguish
between a very noisy connection that has no delays and a clean connection with
long delays, or for that matter a noisy connection with long delays.  The file
receiver responds to a bad packet the same way it responds to a timeout: it
sends a NAK.  The file sender does not know *why* the NAK was sent.  The
situation is exacerbated when packets are corrupted so badly that they are not
recognized as packets -- e.g. when the packet-start character is mangled or
lost.  In that case, we get a timeout anyway, instead of immediately sensing a
checksum/CRC error.

It might be possible for low-level packet-reading code (ttinl) to keep track
of the total number of characters read vs the number of packet characters
read, and if the ratio crosses a certain threshhold, the upper-level code
could infer the line was noisy.  But that still says nothing its delay
characteristics.  So the real question remains: how can you tell what the
delay is?  You can't, without uncorrupted packets.  So hopefully the two
changes above will result in a delay calculation that is more resistent to
noise effects.  ckcfn2.c, 13 Jul 96.  (BUT SEE ENTRY BELOW FOR A SOLUTION.)

A similar problem occurs when we reduce packet lengths because of errors.  We
don't know WHY the error occurred.  If it was because of noise, it is probably
safe to grow packets back to their original size as the noise abates.  But if
it was because of a buffer overflow, it is not safe.  Note that if a buffer is
too small for a packet to begin with, the packet will never get through at
all.  However, there seems to be a fairly common condition in which a packet
of a certain size, say 8K, will often, but not always fail, and yet a packet
of a certain smaller size, say 4K, will hardly ever fail.  In a situation like
this, our current algorithm keeps the packet length oscillating -- we always
go back up to 8K, where it probably fails again, then we go back to 4K, and
on and on.

This effect is exacerbated when using sliding windows.  Suppose we send
sixteen 8K packets before any responses come back.  Then we get 4 ACKs
followed by 12 NAKs.  Each NAK causes us to halve the packet length so we
instantly drop down to 2-byte packets (except there is a minimum of 20 or so).
This is clearly an overreaction.  Probably we only needed to halve it once.
But wait, it gets worse.  Since we can never retransmit a packet in any form
different from its original form, we must retransmit the 12 NAK'd packets in
their original 8K form, which will only make the error count rise, keeping the
length for new packets at a minimum.  So new packets are going out with a
length of 20, while the original 8K ones are being retransmitted over and over
until they all finally get through or the retry limit is exhausted.  Now the
20-byte length creeps back up because there are no more buffer overflows.  But
eventually the threshhold is crossed and a burst of packets goes out that is
too long, and the process repeats: continuous oscillation between 20 bytes and
8192 bytes.

So we need a way to prevent overzealous length reduction at the beginning,
AND we need a way of finding the optimal length to stop at when increasing the
size after errors have subsided.

When we get a NAK or a timeout, how do we know whether to halve the packet
length?  Instead of ALWAYS halving it when there is any kind of error, we'll
make the new length half the length of THE PACKET THAT CAUSED THE ERROR --
the one that was NAK'd, or the one whose ACK we were waiting for.

Thus, in the scenario above, after sending 16 8K packets, and getting lots of
NAKs, we reduce the length of the 17th packet 4K bytes rather than to 8K/2^12,
which is just silly.  If we get an error on the 17th packet, then the 18th
packet will be 2K bytes, and so on.

After reducing the packet length, how far should we increase it after we stop
getting errors?  To answer this, we'll have the sender record the length of
the longest packet that was ACK'd without ever being NAK'd or retransmitted.
The danger here is not being able to recover from a transient condition that
subsequently cleared up.  Or worse: never being able to get past 20 bytes,
because (in the scenario just described), that will be the longest packet that
was ACK'd without ever being NAK'd or retransmitted.

So here is our new strategy for managing packet lengths:

1. Slow start.  If the negotiated packet length is 500 or greater, we start
   our first data packet at 244 bytes (thus ensuring that it fits in a typical
   256-byte buffer).  If it is ACK'd the first time, we double it for the next
   packet, and if that one is ACK'd the first time, we double again, and so on
   up to the maximum negotiated length.  We stop doing this, however, the
   first time we get a NAK or a timeout.  Note that when using sliding
   windows, the first ACK for a data packet might not arrive until after quite
   a few have been sent out at the initial short slow-start length.

2. Each time we get an ACK for a packet that was never NAK'd or retransmitted,
   if it was longer than any previous such packet, we record its length as the
   "best length".  Thus the best length grows during the slow-start period.
   (Obviously we set best length to 0 at the beginning of transaction.)

3. Each time we get an ACK, if the current length for sending packets is less
   than the best length, we increase it by 1/3 the difference between it and
   the best length.

But suppose the best length is small because of a transient condition.  How
can we increase it?  For every nth packet, where n = window slots + 1, we
increase the packet size beyond the best length as a one-shot deal (1/3 of the
way between the best length and the maximum negotiated length).  If we get an
ACK back for it next time around, this automatically bumps up the best length.

