Experiments show that under noisy conditions, the timeouts still get way too
long, e.g. hundreds of seconds when it is perfectly obvious that packets
arrive every 4 or 5 seconds.  A small amount of long overdue thought reveals
that the round-trip time is not what we should be looking at in the general
(more than 1 window slot) case.  Kermit is not X.25, with a separate timer
for each packet (maybe it should be, but that's another story -- but in C you
can't have multiple alarms pending).

Instead of measuring the round-trip time, we should be measuring the interval
at which packets arrive.  When the window size is 1, this is the same as the
round trip time.  But when the window size is > 1, the round trip time is the
amount of time it takes for a whole WINDOW full of packets to arrive, not the
amount of time it should take the next packet to arrive.

So getrtt() was modified to base the packet timeout on the packet arrival
interval rather than the round trip time.  The RTT is still displayed, but
it's not used in the timeout calculation all.  This was a trivial modification
for the file sender, but with the new possibility of a slow start, the
receiver needed a little extra margin of safety during the first round of
packets -- and the cruder it was, the better it worked (if we've received less
than 32 packets, we double the calculated timeout value; otherwise, if less
64, we increase it by 50% -- anything smoother tended to fail).  ckcfn2.c,
