Speaking of LABELed mode... In VMS, if a labeled-mode file transfer failed
between the time it started (but the opening of the file was deferred because
the label info had not been processed yet) and the time it was opened for
real, subsequent close operations would fail (because the file had not been
opened yet), and therefore so would subsequent attempts to open ANY output
file, since zopeni() would think that one was already open.  Fixed for VMS
in ckvfio.c, 22 Sep 96.  Might need to be looked at for OS/2 also, but
probably this does not happen there, since in OS/2 we actually do use file
descriptors and C Library for file i/o, rather than the whole separate
parallel world of RMS used by VMS.

How do we decide whether to prefix a control character these days?  We
reference the prefixing table, ctlp[], using the character as an index.  Guess
what: on some platforms, cltp[c] (where "c" is an _unsigned_ character)
results in conversion of c to a signed integer, and therefore sometimes to an
incorrect array reference, and no doubt an out-of-bounds one too.  The packet
encoder was doing this, and in at least one version -- VAX/VMS C-Kermit built
with VAX C 3.2 -- it resulted in failure to encode file bytes with value 0xff,
which corresponds to Telnet IAC, and therefore failure to transfer any file
that contained this character over a Telnet connection.  On VMS-to-VMS
connections, it resulted in failure to transfer ANY file on a Telnet
connection, because 0xff happens to appear in the labeled-file material for
every file.  Fixed in ckcfns.c, 22 Sep 96.

There was another mysterious problem with VMS C-Kermit's parity changing from
