Finally got the latest sources to build on VAX/VMS5.4/TGV3.3/VAXC3.1 (after
some help from Joellen with the CKVKER.COM file), and glory be, it can
transfer files without having to SET PARITY SPACE.  So maybe I fixed it.

Then again, maybe not -- two reports came in to the contrary only minutes
after the above entry; one applies to a VMS/UNIX serial connection, the other
to a VMS/VMS Telnet connection.  Many hours later... extensive testing and
analysis showed that the real problem was that VMS C-Kermit simply could not
receive files.  It could send just fine, but not receive.  Debug logs showed
incoming data packets badly mangled.  Comparison of a pre-weekend version of
ckvtio.c (when I made the parity fixes) and today's version turned up
virtually no differences outside of the parity-related code.  Close
examination of that code showed that in ttinc() I was using an unsigned char
variable where an int was called for.  And if ttinc() doesn't work right, you
might as well close up shop and go home.  But no, that was would have been too
easy...  Gradually, bit by bit, I backed off on the parity changes.  Now we
can receive files again, but need to SET PARITY SPACE, so we're back where we
were last week.  More hours later...  It seems that when a character comes in
that has its high bit set, and it is returned by ttinc(), netinc(), or
txbufr(), to ttinl(), it gets its sign extended, and so makes it look like
there was a timeout, causing ttinl() to fail.  And yet, there is NO PLACE
where any of these routines returns a character without ANDing it with 0xff or
0x7f.  Real full-width negative numbers are returned only as failure codes.
I'm beginning to smell a DECC rat.  Finally, I went through all those routines
and found all the places where they "return(c & 0xff);" (or whatever) and
changed them all to "return((unsigned)(c & 0xff));".  Now it works again --
even VMS-to-VMS.  21 Oct 96.

