27 Oct 96.

Noticed that the VMS C-Kermit server, when executing REMOTE DIRECTORY, did not
(a) report that a directory file was a directory, and (b) did not strip off
the pathname from each file like the other versions do.  I fixed (b) in
nxtdir(), ckcfns.c, 27 Oct 96.

(a) required adding code to zchki() to report that SYS$BLAH:[USER]BLAH.DIR;1
is a directory (if it is, according to stat() -- I don't know the right
incantations to ask RMS, and evidently nobody else does either, according to
the comments in zchki()).  To check the results of stat() I use S_ISDIR(),
which is not only the proper way to do it, but also apparently the only
portable way -- and note that although VMS lists stat() as a POSIX.1 function,
and POSIX.1 says that S_ISDIR() is a macro, you can't check whether it is
defined with #ifdef because, at least in DECC 5.3, it is not a macro even
though it is there.  Note: I did NOT do anything about .DIR files in isdir(),
because isdir() is mainly used to tell whether its argument string is the name
of a directory that can be used in (say) a CD command.  But [USER]BLAH.DIR;1
does not fit that requirement.  ckvfio.c, 27 Oct 96.

Oops, S_ISDIR() is not defined in DECC 4.0.  I knew it was too easy...  It
is defined in DECC 5.0 and 5.3, so presumably also for 5.2.  It is not defined
in VAXC 3.1.  No way to test for VAX C 3.2. etc etc, #ifdef city, revisited.
See them in zchki(), ckvfio.c, 27 Oct 96.

Noticed that IF DIRECTORY DISK1:[FOO]BLAH.DIR;1 didn't work in VMS.  Made
IF DIR call zchki() for VMS rather than isdir().  ckuus6.c, 27 Oct 96.

Also noticed that you could tell VMS C-Kermit to SEND $DISK1:[FOO]BLAH.DIR;1,
and by golly it would send it -- the directory file itself.  The addition to
zchki() takes care of this.

Back to last night's project.  Discovered that part of the problem with VMS
C-Kermit issuing those "a blah connection appears to be open..." messages is
that it was never built to allow the mainline code access to the ttyfd
variable.  But there's no reason not to, except maybe that you can't really
use it for anything, so I added it.  ckcdeb.h, 27 Oct 96.  (But it didn't help
-- ttyfd is not getting set back to -1 -- but that's a good lead!)

So when I left off, I had VMS C-Kermit detecting when the remote Telnet host
broke the connection, but (a) it would not finish popping back to the prompt
until the user typed a character (a dead giveaway), and (b) you could not
CONNECT back to the host make a new connection.  I can't really list all the
changes I made, but they boil down pretty much to: (1) have all tt*() routines
in ckvtio.c check that ttyfd is > -1 before proceeding AND if it's not a
network connection, also that ttychn is not 0; (2) make sure that contti()
always returns appropriately, in its own insane way; and (3) in the CONNECT
module, if contti() has returned in a way that indicates the connection is
broken, call ttclos() to close our end of the connection and set ttyfd back to
-1, and so on, and have ttclos() and netclos() call ck_cancio() to make sure
all pending reads are canceled, so that a subsequent CONNECT command will find
the connection not open and therefore will open a new one.  It works in UCX
2.0 and various Multinets where I tried it.  The usual suspects, 27 Oct 96.

Replaced memmove() in ckvcvt.c with a stupid homegrown routine, to get rid
of DECC 5.3 warnings on VAX/VMS 7.0.  28 Oct 96.

Fixed \freplace() again -- it was not always null-terminating its result.
