Peter Eichhorn discovered an obscure bug that had always been in the command
parser.  If you type "get" (to start a multiline-GET command), then if you
type a trailing space on the remote filename, then delete it, then type
return, the command parser ignored the whole thing.  cmtxt() is used to parse
the remote filename (since we can't parse it locally as a filename, and since
it might contain spaces.  This was never observed before, because this is one
of the few places where cmtxt() parses a whole line.  Usually cmtxt() is
called only after a keyword has already been entered into the command buffer
(e.g. "echo text").  It turns out the same bug affected ASK and ASKQ.  The fix
was easy -- in cmtxt(), just reset the pointers in the reparse case.
ckucmd.c, 28 Oct 96.

This made me look at GETOK for some reason.  It had similar problems, but
for a different reason.  Fixed in ckuus6.c, 28 Oct 96.

Mike Freeman reported that VMS serial connections don't work after last
night's changes; Carl Friedberg reported the same for LAT.  Evidently I had
failed to apprehend the significance of the schism between ttyfd and ttychn.
One must check ttyfd for positiveness on network connections, and one must
test ttychn for greater-than-zeroness on serial and LAT connections.
ckvtio.c, 28 Oct 96.

The "perror" to print the system error message was #ifdef'd away.  Terry
