Changed prescan() to search the "take path" for the application file (filename
as first command line argument), if the filename is not absolute, just like
the TAKE command does.  Meaningful mainly only for Windows and OS/2, but in
UNIX and VMS (etc) this forces Kermit to look in the home directory if the
file isn't found in the current directory.  The search is done by cmifip(), a
command-parser function.  To use it, we stuff the filename into the command
buffer, followed by a couple CRs to make the function return, But first we
have to call cmdini() because the command-parsing data structures aren't set
up yet.  But that introduced all sorts of problems because cmdini also
executed the init file.  So I split cmdini() into two parts, cmdini() and
doinit(), calling each from the appropriate places, and it all seems to work
fine, at least in UNIX.  ckcmai.c, ckuus4.c, ckuus5.c, 19 Nov 96.

